There is no built-in library in C++ to convert Markdown to HTML. However, you can use a third-party library like `Boost.Markdown` or `Pandoc` to achieve this.

Here is an implementation using `Boost.Markdown`:

```cpp
#include <boost/markdown.hpp>
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <stdexcept>

namespace md = boost::markdown;

std::string md_to_html(std::string markdown) {
    try {
        md::parser parser;
        md::placeholders placeholders;
        md::html_output format;
        return parser(markdown).render(placeholders).as_string(format);
    } catch (const std::exception& e) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Error converting Markdown to HTML: " + std::string(e.what()));
    }
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Hello, World!";
    std::string html = md_to_html(markdown);
    std::cout << html;
    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we include the `Boost.Markdown` header and create a parser instance, a placeholders object, and an HTML output format instance. We then pass the markdown string to the parser and render it with the placeholders object. Finally, we extract the HTML output using the `as_string` method of the HTML output format instance.

Note: Boost.Markdown is a C++ library and it requires the Boost library to be installed in your system. If you do not wish to use `Boost.Markdown`, you can use `Pandoc` (a command-line tool) with `PandocCXX` (a C++ wrapper for `Pandoc`) to achieve the same.

