Here's a function in JavaScript that takes an array of 5 numbers as input and checks if any of them is a valid prime number. If a prime number is found, it prints the number to the console:

```javascript
function isPrime(number) {
  // 1 is not a prime number
  if (number === 1) {
    return false;
  }

  // 2 and 3 are prime numbers
  if (number === 2 || number === 3) {
    return true;
  }

  // All even numbers are not prime
  if (number % 2 === 0) {
    return false;
  }

  // Check odd numbers starting from 3
  for (let I = 3; I <= Math.sqrt(number); I += 2) {
    if (number % I === 0) {
      return false;
    }
  }

  // If no factors are found, the number is prime
  return true;
}

function findPrime(array) {
  for (let I = 0; I < array.length; i++) {
    if (isPrime(array[i])) {
      console.log(array[i]);
      return;
    }
  }
  console.log("No prime number found in the array.");
}

// Example usage
const numbers = [17, 23, 12, 34, 55];
findPrime(numbers);
```

The `isPrime` function is a helper function that checks if a given number is a prime number or not. The `findPrime` function takes an array of numbers, iterates through it, and calls `isPrime` on each number. If a prime number is found, it prints the number to the console and returns from the function. If no prime number is found, it prints a message to the console.

